\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Distribution of VGP TE sequences across the top-level classes (DNA, LTR, LINE, \dots  ). The marked imbalance --- DNA transposons account for $\sim $8\% of all sequences while unannotated/non-transposase sequences dominate --- motivates both the subsampling strategy used to balance binary heads and the inverse square-root weighting used at the superfamily level.}}{10}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:class_distribution}{{1}{10}{Distribution of VGP TE sequences across the top-level classes (DNA, LTR, LINE, \dots ). The marked imbalance --- DNA transposons account for $\sim $8\% of all sequences while unannotated/non-transposase sequences dominate --- motivates both the subsampling strategy used to balance binary heads and the inverse square-root weighting used at the superfamily level}{figure.1}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Superfamily abundances within each top-level TE class. Among DNA transposons, hAT and Tc1 dominate ($>500$ samples each); rare DNA superfamilies (30--100 samples) are the main source of fine-grained classification difficulty. LTR and LINE classes show analogous skew across their own superfamilies.}}{11}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
